[2026-03-02]
- Discussed modular workflow idea: modules A/B/C/D composed per client-specific sequence.
- Key design recommendation:
  - Model module compatibility as a directed graph (not a tree), because modules can have multiple outgoing links and may loop.
  - Store allowed transitions explicitly (e.g., A->[B,D], B->[C,A], C->[D], D->[]).
  - Provide a validator to check whether a requested path is valid before runtime execution.
  - Keep each module with a strict input/output contract so connections are predictable.

[2026-03-02]
- Requirement clarified: some modules must run multiple times in a single process.
- Flow-engine implication:
  - Allow repeated nodes/cycles in execution paths.
  - Add safety controls (max_steps, per-module max_visits, and explicit stop conditions) to prevent infinite loops.

[2026-03-02]
- Clarified implementation strategy when no real modules exist yet:
  - Build the flow engine first as framework-agnostic core infrastructure.
  - Define module contract/interface (execute + metadata) and transition graph schema.
  - Use placeholder/mock modules for early validation and tests.
  - Integrate real modules later by implementing the same contract.

[2026-03-02]
- Implemented standalone-first reusable flow engine in core to support client-custom module sequences before real modules exist.
- New core components:
  - FlowGraph: directed transition map with validation (validate_path, can_transition, next_options).
  - FlowEngine: executes fixed paths (run_path) and rule-driven paths (run_auto).
  - ModuleOutcome: standardized module output (context_updates, next_module, stop, reason).
  - Safety controls: max_steps and max_visits_per_module to permit repeats while preventing infinite loops.
- Integration contract:
  - FlowModule protocol defines framework-agnostic execute(context) interface.
  - Real modules can be added later without changing engine logic.
